<subSubSection id="78DA6565FFBEFF9DFEBFF8C021DAFE27" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="337" pageId="1" pageNumber="336" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="307F36EEFFBEFF9DFEBFF8C021DAFE27" blockId="1.[264,1322,1833,1900]" lastBlockId="2.[264,1324,284,1870]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="337" pageId="1" pageNumber="336">
<emphasis id="02B4EAFCFFBEFF9EFEBFF8C021CBF8B2" bold="true" box="[264,392,1873,1899]" pageId="1" pageNumber="336">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Small Heteropodinae (body length 
<quantity id="F7389B0BFFBEFF9EFCFBF8C323A2F8B5" box="[844,993,1874,1900]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.1" metricValueMax="7.5" metricValueMin="4.7" pageId="1" pageNumber="336" unit="mm" value="6.1" valueMax="7.5" valueMin="4.7">4.7–7.5 mm</quantity>
) without lateral spines on metatarsi I­II. Male cymbium retrobasally with bent spur, embolus with loop running transversally to plane of alveolus. Females with spirally coiled copulatory openings similar to those in 
<taxonomicName id="F7C04D6DFFBDFF9DFE52FEFD2349FE5F" authority="Simon 1880" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1880" box="[485,778,364,390]" class="Arachnida" family="Sparassidae" genus="Spariolenus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="02B4EAFCFFBDFF9DFE52FEFD2232FE5C" box="[485,625,364,389]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">Spariolenus</emphasis>
Simon 
<number id="860824C9FFBDFF9DFD7AFEFD2349FE5F" box="[717,778,364,390]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="1880.0">1880</number>
</taxonomicName>
, differing from the latter in having a pit in the posterior part of the median septum. Internal duct system with broad lateral loops and subsequent narrow ducts, the latter running parallel or slightly converging close to the median line.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="78DA6565FFBDFF9DFE8FFD9A22EAFD37" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="307F36EEFFBDFF9DFE8FFD9A22EAFD37" blockId="2.[264,1324,284,1870]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">
<emphasis id="02B4EAFCFFBDFF9DFE8FFD9A2187FDFC" bold="true" box="[312,452,523,549]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">Etymology.</emphasis>
The genus name is a word consisting of the family name of Prof. Dr Jochen Martens and the last part of the genus name 
<taxonomicName id="F7C04D6DFFBDFF9DFCD3FDA523ACFD94" box="[868,1007,564,589]" class="Arachnida" family="Sparassidae" genus="Heteropoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="02B4EAFCFFBDFF9DFCD3FDA523ACFD94" box="[868,1007,564,589]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">Heteropoda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; it is feminine in gender. It pays tribute to Prof. Martens and his scientific contributions to the Arachnology and the zoogeography of Asian mountain ranges (especially Himalaya). Moreover, I express my personal thanks towards Prof. Martens for supervising and guiding me in my first years of taxonomic and systematic research.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="78DA6565FFBDFF9CFE8FFD6D245FFEEF" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="338" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" type="description">
<paragraph id="307F36EEFFBDFF9DFE8FFD6D2493FB17" blockId="2.[264,1324,284,1870]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">
<emphasis id="02B4EAFCFFBDFF9DFE8FFD6D218CFCCF" bold="true" box="[312,463,764,790]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">Description.</emphasis>
Male cymbium with prolateral bulge (PB), giving a unique general appearance (
<figureCitation id="A8FB2A6BFFBDFF9DFE2CFCB52246FCE7" box="[411,517,804,830]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="4.[264,382,1776,1800]" captionTargetBox="[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Martensopoda transversa gen. nov., sp. nov., ♂ holotype from Cardamon Hills, India (PJ 1771). 1 – 5 Left male pedipalp (1 prolateral, 2, 5 ventral, 3 retrolateral, 4 dorsal); 6 Tip of embolus, prolateral; 7 Trilobate membrane of left leg IV, dorsal; 8 Dorsal shield of prosoma, dorsal. C conductor, E embolus, EA embolic apophysis, PB prolateral bulge, SP spur of cymbium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174021/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">Figs 2, 5</figureCitation>
). Embolus with filiform apophysis, the latter arising on the ventrally bent part of the embolus (
<figureCitation id="A8FB2A6BFFBDFF9DFDF6FCDD22C8FCBF" box="[577,651,844,870]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="4.[264,382,1776,1800]" captionTargetBox="[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Martensopoda transversa gen. nov., sp. nov., ♂ holotype from Cardamon Hills, India (PJ 1771). 1 – 5 Left male pedipalp (1 prolateral, 2, 5 ventral, 3 retrolateral, 4 dorsal); 6 Tip of embolus, prolateral; 7 Trilobate membrane of left leg IV, dorsal; 8 Dorsal shield of prosoma, dorsal. C conductor, E embolus, EA embolic apophysis, PB prolateral bulge, SP spur of cymbium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174021/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">
Fig. 
<number id="860824C9FFBDFF9DFDCDFCDD22C8FCBF" box="[634,651,844,870]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
). Tip of embolic apophysis serrated (
<figureCitation id="A8FB2A6BFFBDFF9DFBFAFCDD24D4FCBF" box="[1101,1175,844,870]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="4.[264,382,1776,1800]" captionTargetBox="[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Martensopoda transversa gen. nov., sp. nov., ♂ holotype from Cardamon Hills, India (PJ 1771). 1 – 5 Left male pedipalp (1 prolateral, 2, 5 ventral, 3 retrolateral, 4 dorsal); 6 Tip of embolus, prolateral; 7 Trilobate membrane of left leg IV, dorsal; 8 Dorsal shield of prosoma, dorsal. C conductor, E embolus, EA embolic apophysis, PB prolateral bulge, SP spur of cymbium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174021/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">
Fig. 
<number id="860824C9FFBDFF9DFB31FCDD24D4FCBF" box="[1158,1175,844,870]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
). Conductor strongly reduced (C in 
<figureCitation id="A8FB2A6BFFBDFF9DFDABFCE52227FC57" box="[540,612,884,910]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="4.[264,382,1776,1800]" captionTargetBox="[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Martensopoda transversa gen. nov., sp. nov., ♂ holotype from Cardamon Hills, India (PJ 1771). 1 – 5 Left male pedipalp (1 prolateral, 2, 5 ventral, 3 retrolateral, 4 dorsal); 6 Tip of embolus, prolateral; 7 Trilobate membrane of left leg IV, dorsal; 8 Dorsal shield of prosoma, dorsal. C conductor, E embolus, EA embolic apophysis, PB prolateral bulge, SP spur of cymbium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174021/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">
Fig. 
<number id="860824C9FFBDFF9DFDE4FCE52227FC57" box="[595,612,884,910]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
). Subtegulum visible in prolateral half of bulb (
<figureCitation id="A8FB2A6BFFBDFF9DFB28FCE524A6FC57" box="[1183,1253,884,910]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="4.[264,382,1776,1800]" captionTargetBox="[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Martensopoda transversa gen. nov., sp. nov., ♂ holotype from Cardamon Hills, India (PJ 1771). 1 – 5 Left male pedipalp (1 prolateral, 2, 5 ventral, 3 retrolateral, 4 dorsal); 6 Tip of embolus, prolateral; 7 Trilobate membrane of left leg IV, dorsal; 8 Dorsal shield of prosoma, dorsal. C conductor, E embolus, EA embolic apophysis, PB prolateral bulge, SP spur of cymbium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174021/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">
Fig. 
<number id="860824C9FFBDFF9DFB60FCE524A6FC57" box="[1239,1253,884,910]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
); this fact and the extraordinary conformation of the embolus resulting from a rotation of the whole bulb of about 
<number id="860824C9FFBDFF9DFDB4FC552260FC07" box="[515,547,964,990]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="90.0">90</number>
° in a retrolateral direction (ventrally). RTA long and not divided into two parts as in other genera of Heteropodinae, its tip widened in retrolateral view (
<figureCitation id="A8FB2A6BFFBDFF9DFEA7FB852138FBF7" box="[272,379,1044,1070]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="4.[264,382,1776,1800]" captionTargetBox="[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Martensopoda transversa gen. nov., sp. nov., ♂ holotype from Cardamon Hills, India (PJ 1771). 1 – 5 Left male pedipalp (1 prolateral, 2, 5 ventral, 3 retrolateral, 4 dorsal); 6 Tip of embolus, prolateral; 7 Trilobate membrane of left leg IV, dorsal; 8 Dorsal shield of prosoma, dorsal. C conductor, E embolus, EA embolic apophysis, PB prolateral bulge, SP spur of cymbium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174021/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">
Figs 
<number id="860824C9FFBDFF9DFEFCFB852138FBF7" box="[331,379,1044,1070]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="2.5" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="2.0">2–3</number>
</figureCitation>
). Female epiygne with anteriorly and posteriorly diverging septum and posterior median pocket (PP in 
<figureCitation id="A8FB2A6BFFBDFF9DFD91FBAD2237FB8F" box="[550,628,1084,1110]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 12" captionStartId="5.[264,382,1109,1133]" captionTargetBox="[289,1303,318,1091]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[289,1304,318,1092]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 12. Martensopoda transversa gen. nov., sp. nov., ΨΨ paratypes from Cardamon Hills, Kerala, India (9 – 10, 12 PJ 1772, 11 PJ 1775). 9, 11 Epigyne, ventral; 10 Internal duct system, dorsal; 12 Schematic course of internal duct system, dorsal. LL lateral loops of internal duct system, MS median septum, PA pit anterior to septum, PP pit posterior to septum, R spiral rim of copulatory opening." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174022/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">
Fig. 
<number id="860824C9FFBDFF9DFDD4FBAD2237FB8F" box="[611,628,1084,1110]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
). Epigynal field roundish to transversally oval, without anterior bands (
<figureCitation id="A8FB2A6BFFBDFF9DFE7DFBF5225FFBA7" box="[458,540,1124,1150]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 12" captionStartId="5.[264,382,1109,1133]" captionTargetBox="[289,1303,318,1091]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[289,1304,318,1092]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 12. Martensopoda transversa gen. nov., sp. nov., ΨΨ paratypes from Cardamon Hills, Kerala, India (9 – 10, 12 PJ 1772, 11 PJ 1775). 9, 11 Epigyne, ventral; 10 Internal duct system, dorsal; 12 Schematic course of internal duct system, dorsal. LL lateral loops of internal duct system, MS median septum, PA pit anterior to septum, PP pit posterior to septum, R spiral rim of copulatory opening." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174022/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">Figs 9</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="A8FB2A6BFFBDFF9DFD99FBF5220DFBA7" box="[558,590,1124,1150]" captionStart="FIGURES 13 – 21" captionStartId="7.[264,382,1726,1750]" captionTargetBox="[284,1314,320,1709]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[284,1314,320,1709]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 13 – 21. Martensopoda minuscula (Reimoser 1934) comb. nov., ΨΨ from Palni Hills, Tamil Nadu, India (13 – 16 PJ 1776, 17 PJ 1777, 18 – 19 lectotype PJ 1705, 21 – 21 paralectotype PJ 1706). 13, 17 – 18, 20 Epigyne, ventral; 14 – 15 Internal duct system, dorsal (15 right half partly broken and shifted); 16 Schematic course of internal duct system, dorsal; 19, 21 Left chelicera, showing dentition, ventral. R spiral rim of copulatory opening." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174023/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">13</figureCitation>
). Internal duct system with a lateral coil similar to that in 
<taxonomicName id="F7C04D6DFFBDFF9DFEBFFB1D213EFB7C" box="[264,381,1164,1189]" class="Arachnida" family="Sparassidae" genus="Barylestis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="02B4EAFCFFBDFF9DFEBFFB1D213EFB7C" box="[264,381,1164,1189]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">Barylestis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. One part of the duct system, functionally situated behind the first windings and the fertilisation ducts, running parallel along the median line (
<figureCitation id="A8FB2A6BFFBDFF9DFBB9FB252429FB17" box="[1038,1130,1204,1230]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 12" captionStartId="5.[264,382,1109,1133]" captionTargetBox="[289,1303,318,1091]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[289,1304,318,1092]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 12. Martensopoda transversa gen. nov., sp. nov., ΨΨ paratypes from Cardamon Hills, Kerala, India (9 – 10, 12 PJ 1772, 11 PJ 1775). 9, 11 Epigyne, ventral; 10 Internal duct system, dorsal; 12 Schematic course of internal duct system, dorsal. LL lateral loops of internal duct system, MS median septum, PA pit anterior to septum, PP pit posterior to septum, R spiral rim of copulatory opening." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174022/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">Figs 10</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="A8FB2A6BFFBDFF9DFBC1FB252480FB17" box="[1142,1219,1204,1230]" captionStart="FIGURES 13 – 21" captionStartId="7.[264,382,1726,1750]" captionTargetBox="[284,1314,320,1709]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[284,1314,320,1709]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 13 – 21. Martensopoda minuscula (Reimoser 1934) comb. nov., ΨΨ from Palni Hills, Tamil Nadu, India (13 – 16 PJ 1776, 17 PJ 1777, 18 – 19 lectotype PJ 1705, 21 – 21 paralectotype PJ 1706). 13, 17 – 18, 20 Epigyne, ventral; 14 – 15 Internal duct system, dorsal (15 right half partly broken and shifted); 16 Schematic course of internal duct system, dorsal; 19, 21 Left chelicera, showing dentition, ventral. R spiral rim of copulatory opening." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174023/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">
14– 
<number id="860824C9FFBDFF9DFB11FB252480FB17" box="[1190,1219,1204,1230]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="15.0">15</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="307F36EEFFBDFF9DFE8FFB4D2304FA9F" blockId="2.[264,1324,284,1870]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">
Eye size ratios typical for Heteropodinae: lateral larger than median eyes, particular posterior eyes only slightly larger than anterior eyes. DS length / DS width = 
<number id="860824C9FFBDFF9DFB72FA9524A9FAC7" box="[1221,1258,1284,1310]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="1.1">1.1</number>
(1.0, n= 
<number id="860824C9FFBDFF9DFE99FABD217AFA9F" box="[302,313,1324,1350]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="1.0">1</number>
); DS width / anterior width of DS = 
<number id="860824C9FFBDFF9DFD50FABD2307FA9F" box="[743,836,1324,1350]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="1.7999999999999998" valueMax="1.9" valueMin="1.7">1.7–1.9</number>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="307F36EEFFBDFF9DFE8FFAC524A5F927" blockId="2.[264,1324,284,1870]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">
Cheliceral teeth variable: basic pattern for Heteropodinae 
<number id="860824C9FFBDFF9DFC54FAC523B1FAB7" box="[995,1010,1364,1390]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="3.0">3</number>
anterior, 
<number id="860824C9FFBDFF9DFBD4FAC52432FAB7" box="[1123,1137,1364,1390]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="4.0">4</number>
posterior teeth; 
<taxonomicName id="F7C04D6DFFBDFF9DFEBFFAED21F0FA4C" box="[264,435,1404,1429]" class="Arachnida" family="Sparassidae" genus="Martensopoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="02B4EAFCFFBDFF9DFEBFFAED21F0FA4C" box="[264,435,1404,1429]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">Martensopoda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="02B4EAFCFFBDFF9DFE0CFAED2269FA4F" bold="true" box="[443,554,1404,1430]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="19875787FFBDFF9DFE0CFAED2269FA4F" box="[443,554,1404,1430]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
: 
<number id="860824C9FFBDFF9DFD8DFAED2225FA4F" box="[570,614,1404,1430]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="3.0" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="2.0">2–4</number>
anterior, 
<number id="860824C9FFBDFF9DFD6FFAED2347FA4F" box="[728,772,1404,1430]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="4.0" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="3.0">3–5</number>
posterior teeth (
<figureCitation id="A8FB2A6BFFBDFF9DFC72FAED240CFA4F" box="[965,1103,1404,1430]" captionStart="FIGURES 13 – 21" captionStartId="7.[264,382,1726,1750]" captionTargetBox="[284,1314,320,1709]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[284,1314,320,1709]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 13 – 21. Martensopoda minuscula (Reimoser 1934) comb. nov., ΨΨ from Palni Hills, Tamil Nadu, India (13 – 16 PJ 1776, 17 PJ 1777, 18 – 19 lectotype PJ 1705, 21 – 21 paralectotype PJ 1706). 13, 17 – 18, 20 Epigyne, ventral; 14 – 15 Internal duct system, dorsal (15 right half partly broken and shifted); 16 Schematic course of internal duct system, dorsal; 19, 21 Left chelicera, showing dentition, ventral. R spiral rim of copulatory opening." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174023/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">Figs 19, 21</figureCitation>
). Posterior margin of chelicerae between teeth and fang with one long curved bristle, apparently typical within Heteropodinae (cf. 
<bibRefCitation id="54514B1FFFBDFF9DFD8AFA5D2283FA3F" author="Levy" box="[573,704,1484,1510]" pageId="2" pageNumber="345" refString="Levy, G. (1989) The family of huntsman spiders in Israel with annotations on spiders of the Middle East (Araneae: Sparassidae). Journal of Zoology, 217, 127 - 176." type="journal article" year="1989">
Levy 
<number id="860824C9FFBDFF9DFD36FA5D2283FA3F" box="[641,704,1484,1510]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="1989.0">1989</number>
</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 
<number id="860824C9FFBDFF9DFD4CFA5D2368FA3F" box="[763,811,1484,1510]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="130.0">130</number>
). Female palpus claw with 
<number id="860824C9FFBDFF9DFBDCFA5D24D4FA3F" box="[1131,1175,1484,1510]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="7.0" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="6.0">6–8</number>
teeth; shape of palpal and leg claw typical for Heteropodinae (
<figureCitation id="A8FB2A6BFFBDFF9DFCEEFA6523A0F9D7" box="[857,995,1524,1550]" captionStart="FIGURES 22 – 26. 22 – 25" captionStartId="8.[264,382,1079,1103]" captionTargetBox="[282,1305,326,1053]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[282,1305,326,1053]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 22 – 26. 22 – 25 Martensopoda minuscula (Reimoser 1934) comb. nov., ΨΨ from Palni Hills, Tamil Nadu, India (22 – 23 PJ 1776, 24 – 25 PJ 1778). 26 Martensopoda transversa gen. nov., sp. nov., Ψ paratype from Cardamon Hills, Kerala, India (PJ 1772). 22 Claw of right pedipalpus, retrolateral; 23 Prolateral claw of right leg I, prolateral; 24, 26 Dorsal shield of prosoma, dorsal; 25 Sternum, ventral." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174024/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">
Figs 
<number id="860824C9FFBDFF9DFC22FA6523A0F9D7" box="[917,995,1524,1550]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="22.5" valueMax="23.0" valueMin="22.0">22–23</number>
</figureCitation>
). Leg length pattern (
<number id="860824C9FFBDFF9DFB54FA652563F9D7" box="[1251,1312,1524,1550]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="2413.0">2413</number>
) fits scheme found by 
<bibRefCitation id="54514B1FFFBDFF9DFDB9F98D22E0F9EF" author="Jager" box="[526,675,1564,1590]" pageId="2" pageNumber="345" refString="Jager, P. (2001) Diversitat der Riesenkrabbenspinnen im Himalaya. Uber eine Radiation zweier Gattungen in den Schneetropen. (Araneae: Sparassidae: Heteropodinae). Courier Forshungsinstitut Senckenberg, 232, 1 - 136." type="journal article" year="2001">
Jäger (
<number id="860824C9FFBDFF9DFDEAF98D22D9F9EF" box="[605,666,1564,1590]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="2001.0">2001</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
for other Heteropodinae (
<number id="860824C9FFBDFF9DFC6BF98D245BF9EF" box="[988,1048,1564,1590]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="2413.0">2413</number>
for specimens &lt;
<quantity id="F7389B0BFFBDFF9DFB5BF98D256BF9EF" box="[1260,1320,1564,1590]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" unit="mm" value="5.0">5mm</quantity>
DS length, 
<number id="860824C9FFBDFF9DFE3CF9D52185F987" box="[395,454,1604,1630]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="2143.0">2143</number>
&gt; 
<quantity id="F7389B0BFFBDFF9DFE6BF9D5225AF987" box="[476,537,1604,1630]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" unit="mm" value="5.0">5mm</quantity>
DS length). Legs showing general trend for reducing spines: femur (retrolateral), tibiae I–II (prolateral), tibiae IV (retrolateral). Patella spination variable: 000–001. Metatarsus III additionally to metatarsus IV with additional distal median ventral spine; metatarsus III variable: 2014, 2024, 
<number id="860824C9FFBDFF9DFCDEF92D23E4F90F" box="[873,935,1724,1750]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="2025.0">2025</number>
. Trochanters with ventral notch. Trilobate membrane with median hook and lateral projection of similar size (
<figureCitation id="A8FB2A6BFFBDFF9DFB27F9752494F927" box="[1168,1239,1764,1790]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="4.[264,382,1776,1800]" captionTargetBox="[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Martensopoda transversa gen. nov., sp. nov., ♂ holotype from Cardamon Hills, India (PJ 1771). 1 – 5 Left male pedipalp (1 prolateral, 2, 5 ventral, 3 retrolateral, 4 dorsal); 6 Tip of embolus, prolateral; 7 Trilobate membrane of left leg IV, dorsal; 8 Dorsal shield of prosoma, dorsal. C conductor, E embolus, EA embolic apophysis, PB prolateral bulge, SP spur of cymbium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174021/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">
Fig. 
<number id="860824C9FFBDFF9DFB71F9752494F927" box="[1222,1239,1764,1790]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="307F36EEFFBDFF9CFE8FF89D245FFEEF" blockId="2.[264,1324,284,1870]" lastBlockId="3.[264,1323,284,950]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="338" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">
Generally light coloured to pale spiders. Dorsal shield of prosoma and sternum with dark, partly faint markings, eyes with distinct dark patches (
<figureCitation id="A8FB2A6BFFBDFF9DFC5FF8A52474F897" box="[1000,1079,1844,1870]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="4.[264,382,1776,1800]" captionTargetBox="[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Martensopoda transversa gen. nov., sp. nov., ♂ holotype from Cardamon Hills, India (PJ 1771). 1 – 5 Left male pedipalp (1 prolateral, 2, 5 ventral, 3 retrolateral, 4 dorsal); 6 Tip of embolus, prolateral; 7 Trilobate membrane of left leg IV, dorsal; 8 Dorsal shield of prosoma, dorsal. C conductor, E embolus, EA embolic apophysis, PB prolateral bulge, SP spur of cymbium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174021/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">Figs 8</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="A8FB2A6BFFBDFF9DFBFFF8A524D4F897" box="[1096,1175,1844,1870]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 22 – 26. 22 – 25" captionStart-1="FIGURES 27 – 30. 27 – 28" captionStartId-0="8.[264,382,1079,1103]" captionStartId-1="9.[264,382,1344,1368]" captionTargetBox-0="[282,1305,326,1053]" captionTargetBox-1="[276,1309,486,1318]" captionTargetId-0="figure@8.[282,1305,326,1053]" captionTargetId-1="figure@9.[276,1310,486,1318]" captionTargetPageId-0="8" captionTargetPageId-1="9" captionText-0="FIGURES 22 – 26. 22 – 25 Martensopoda minuscula (Reimoser 1934) comb. nov., ΨΨ from Palni Hills, Tamil Nadu, India (22 – 23 PJ 1776, 24 – 25 PJ 1778). 26 Martensopoda transversa gen. nov., sp. nov., Ψ paratype from Cardamon Hills, Kerala, India (PJ 1772). 22 Claw of right pedipalpus, retrolateral; 23 Prolateral claw of right leg I, prolateral; 24, 26 Dorsal shield of prosoma, dorsal; 25 Sternum, ventral." captionText-1="FIGURES 27 – 30. 27 – 28 Martensopoda transversa gen. nov., sp. nov., ♂ holotype, ΨΨ paratypes from Cardamon Hills, Kerala, India. 29 – 30 Martensopoda minuscula (Reimoser 1934) comb. nov., ΨΨ from Palni Hills, Tamil Nadu, India (27, 29 dorsal aspect; 28, 30 ventral aspect). See illustrations for identification (PJ) number." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/174024/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/174025/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="337">
24– 
<number id="860824C9FFBDFF9DFBCFF8A524D4F897" box="[1144,1175,1844,1870]" pageId="2" pageNumber="337" value="30.0">30</number>
</figureCitation>
). Chelicerae with longitudinal stripes typical for Heteropodinae (
<figureCitation id="A8FB2A6BFFBCFF9CFCDEFE8D23F7FEEF" box="[873,948,284,310]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="4.[264,382,1776,1800]" captionTargetBox="[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[323,1268,326,1762]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Martensopoda transversa gen. nov., sp. nov., ♂ holotype from Cardamon Hills, India (PJ 1771). 1 – 5 Left male pedipalp (1 prolateral, 2, 5 ventral, 3 retrolateral, 4 dorsal); 6 Tip of embolus, prolateral; 7 Trilobate membrane of left leg IV, dorsal; 8 Dorsal shield of prosoma, dorsal. C conductor, E embolus, EA embolic apophysis, PB prolateral bulge, SP spur of cymbium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174021/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="338">Figs 8</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="A8FB2A6BFFBCFF9CFC76FE8D244DFEEF" box="[961,1038,284,310]" captionStart="FIGURES 22 – 26. 22 – 25" captionStartId="8.[264,382,1079,1103]" captionTargetBox="[282,1305,326,1053]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[282,1305,326,1053]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 22 – 26. 22 – 25 Martensopoda minuscula (Reimoser 1934) comb. nov., ΨΨ from Palni Hills, Tamil Nadu, India (22 – 23 PJ 1776, 24 – 25 PJ 1778). 26 Martensopoda transversa gen. nov., sp. nov., Ψ paratype from Cardamon Hills, Kerala, India (PJ 1772). 22 Claw of right pedipalpus, retrolateral; 23 Prolateral claw of right leg I, prolateral; 24, 26 Dorsal shield of prosoma, dorsal; 25 Sternum, ventral." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174024/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="338">
24, 
<number id="860824C9FFBCFF9CFC5AFE8D244DFEEF" box="[1005,1038,284,310]" pageId="3" pageNumber="338" value="26.0">26</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
